## Cold War Context and Ideological Conflict

### The Global Cold War Rivalry

The Vietnam War must be understood within the broader context of the Cold War, a geopolitical and ideological rivalry between the United States and its Western allies and the communist bloc led by the Soviet Union and China. After World War II, the U.S. adopted a policy of containment aimed at preventing the spread of communism worldwide, perceiving it as a threat to democracy and capitalism ([TheVietnamWar.info](https://thevietnamwar.info/why-did-the-vietnam-war-start/)).

The rise of communist China in 1949 and the Soviet Union’s support for North Vietnam intensified U.S. fears that communism would spread throughout Southeast Asia. The "Domino Theory," articulated by President Dwight D. Eisenhower, posited that if one country in the region fell to communism, neighboring countries would follow, threatening U.S. strategic interests and allies such as Japan, Taiwan, Australia, and New Zealand ([History.com](https://www.history.com/topics/vietnam-war/vietnam-war-history)).

### U.S. Involvement and Containment Policy

American involvement began incrementally, starting with economic and military aid to the French in 1950 under President Harry S. Truman, who supported the French effort to retain Indochina against communist forces. Following the French defeat, the U.S. refused to recognize the communist government in North Vietnam and instead supported the anti-communist government in South Vietnam ([Encyclopedia.com](https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/asia-and-africa/southeast-asia-history/vietnam-war)).

The U.S. supported South Vietnam politically and militarily, initially through aid and advisors, and later through direct military intervention. Presidents John F. Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson escalated U.S. involvement, with Kennedy increasing aid and troops in the early 1960s, and Johnson committing large numbers of combat troops following the Gulf of Tonkin incident in 1964 ([LifePersona](https://www.lifepersona.com/vietnam-war-the-major-causes-and-consequences); [WorldAtlas](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/why-did-the-vietnam-war-start.html)).

