## Vietnamese Internal Dynamics and the Role of the Viet Cong

### Division and Conflict within Vietnam

The division of Vietnam into North and South created two ideologically opposed states. North Vietnam, led by Ho Chi Minh and supported by communist allies, sought to reunify the country under communism. South Vietnam, backed by the U.S. and other Western nations, aimed to establish a non-communist independent state.

The National Liberation Front (NLF), also known as the Viet Cong, was a communist guerrilla group operating in South Vietnam, supported by North Vietnam. The Viet Cong waged a guerrilla war against the South Vietnamese government and U.S. forces, aiming to overthrow the South Vietnamese regime and reunify the country ([WorldAtlas](https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/why-did-the-vietnam-war-start.html)).

### Political Instability in South Vietnam

South Vietnam experienced political instability, including the overthrow and assassination of President Ngo Dinh Diem in 1963, which was supported covertly by the U.S. This led to a series of weak military governments, complicating the U.S. mission and undermining South Vietnamese legitimacy ([LifePersona](https://www.lifepersona.com/vietnam-war-the-major-causes-and-consequences)).

